webpackJsonp([0xc3f8fd2c2f1],{327:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{site:{siteMetadata:{title:"Rafael Belliard - Software developer",author:"Rafael Belliard"}},markdownRemark:{id:"/home/rafael/play/rebelliard.github.io/src/pages/blog/2016-07-16-response-to-react-design-principles-interpretation-by-react-members/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>Yesterday, I shared <a href="/blog/react-driven-by-facebook-principle-concerns">how concerned</a> I was with Reactâ€™s\n<a href="https://facebook.github.io/react/contributing/design-principles.html">Design Principles</a>.\nToday, Iâ€™d like to share the response I received from <a href="https://twitter.com/dan_abramov">@dan_abramov</a>\nâ€”a member of the React teamâ€” regarding my interpretation of these principles.</p>\n<p>I hope this helps anyone who felt as conflicted as I did.</p>\n<h2>Response</h2>\n<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/rebelliard">@rebelliard</a> That Facebook heavily uses React in production (unlike Parse) is exactly why I think community can bet on it.</p>&mdash; Dan Abramov (@dan_abramov) <a href="https://twitter.com/dan_abramov/status/754278530817617921">July 16, 2016</a></blockquote>\n<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-conversation="none" data-lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/rebelliard">@rebelliard</a> Community is obviously important but ultimately projects with business value are those that companies keep developing.</p>&mdash; Dan Abramov (@dan_abramov) <a href="https://twitter.com/dan_abramov/status/754278857331662848">July 16, 2016</a></blockquote>\n<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-conversation="none" data-lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/rebelliard">@rebelliard</a> So on the contrary, I think you should have been concerned if Facebook didn&#39;t use React and maintained it for image purposes ğŸ˜‰</p>&mdash; Dan Abramov (@dan_abramov) <a href="https://twitter.com/dan_abramov/status/754279261805109248">July 16, 2016</a></blockquote>\n<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-conversation="none" data-lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/rebelliard">@rebelliard</a> There is also some sort of misunderstanding here. Post says â€œboth externally and internallyâ€. <a href="https://t.co/ku7DG0j5S0">pic.twitter.com/ku7DG0j5S0</a></p>&mdash; Dan Abramov (@dan_abramov) <a href="https://twitter.com/dan_abramov/status/754280725076119552">July 16, 2016</a></blockquote>\n<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-conversation="none" data-lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/rebelliard">@rebelliard</a> â€œExternallyâ€ *is* the community. Sorry if this wasnâ€™t clear. I can change the wording to be more direct.</p>&mdash; Dan Abramov (@dan_abramov) <a href="https://twitter.com/dan_abramov/status/754281037891592192">July 16, 2016</a></blockquote>\n<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/rebelliard">@rebelliard</a> I wrote a comment</p>&mdash; Dan Abramov (@dan_abramov) <a href="https://twitter.com/dan_abramov/status/754285961845022720">July 16, 2016</a></blockquote>\n<ul>\n<li>The comment can be read <a href="https://disqus.com/home/discussion/rebelliard/reacts_driven_by_facebook_principle_concerns/#comment-2786435370">here</a>.\nItâ€™s good stuff.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>About Parse</h2>\n<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/rebelliard">@rebelliard</a> <a href="https://twitter.com/dan_abramov">@dan_abramov</a> Parse servers will be decommissioned in a year and the entire stack was made open source so you can run your own</p>&mdash; Vjeux (@Vjeux) <a href="https://twitter.com/Vjeux/status/754317380386304004">July 16, 2016</a></blockquote>\n<blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-conversation="none" data-lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/rebelliard">@rebelliard</a> <a href="https://twitter.com/dan_abramov">@dan_abramov</a> I&#39;ve rarely seen such a graceful shut down of a service before</p>&mdash; Vjeux (@Vjeux) <a href="https://twitter.com/Vjeux/status/754317595143049222">July 16, 2016</a></blockquote>\n<h2>Closing thoughts</h2>\n<p>\n  <img src="/public/images/blog/2016-07-16/not-even-mad.jpg" height="185" alt="That\'s amazing.">\n</p>\n<p>I thank <a href="https://twitter.com/dan_abramov">@dan_abramov</a> for taking the time to clarify what they meant.\nIt certainly didnâ€™t occur to me that they kept an ear to the ground and I could <em>just ask</em>,\nwhich gives me a sense of relief and quite frankly, makes me <strong>even more</strong> interested\nin the library than I previously was.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://twitter.com/dan_abramov/status/754278530817617921">Response</a> on Twitter.</li>\n<li><a href="react-driven-by-facebook-principle-concerns#comment-2786435370">Response</a> to my original post.</li>\n<li><a href="https://github.com/facebook/react/pull/7292/files">Changeset</a> <em>further</em> clarifying\nthe original article.</li>\n</ul>',frontmatter:{title:"Response to my interpretation of React's â€œDesign Principlesâ€",teaser:"Clarification of my concerns about React's â€œDesign Principlesâ€ by members of the React team.",description:"Clarification of my concerns about React's â€œDesign Principlesâ€ by members of the React team.",image:"2016-07-16/react-logo-reload.png",date:"July 16, 2016",permalink:"/blog/response-to-react-design-principles-interpretation-by-react-members/",tags:["React"]}}},pathContext:{slug:"/blog/response-to-react-design-principles-interpretation-by-react-members/",previous:{fields:{slug:"/blog/react-driven-by-facebook-principle-concerns/"},frontmatter:{title:"React's â€œDriven by Facebookâ€ principle concerns me",teaser:"React's â€œDesign Principlesâ€ article gave me a rollercoaster of emotions that reminded me of Facebook's ill-fated Parse service.",description:"React's â€œDesign Principlesâ€ article gave me a rollercoaster of emotions that reminded me of Facebook's ill-fated Parse service.",tags:["React"],image:"2016-07-15/react-logo.png",redirectFrom:null}},next:{fields:{slug:"/blog/8-tips-to-become-an-effective-remote-developer/"},frontmatter:{title:"8 tips to become an effective remote developer",teaser:"For you to evolve as a developer, you need to be a self-starter and make it a point to keep yourself active and in constant state of learning.",description:"For you to evolve as a developer, you need to be a self-starter and make it a point to keep yourself active and in constant state of learning.",tags:["Growth"],image:"2016-07-28/remote-meeting.jpg",redirectFrom:null}}}}}});
